data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code directly:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your manual `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` construction **won't compile**. Replace with a plain lambda:

```csharp
// EF Core 10
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

All that expression-tree machinery is eliminated — `SetPropertyCalls` now uses `Action<>` instead of `Expression<Func<>>`.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — uniquified & full-path nested

Two sub-changes:

- **Duplicate property names across complex types** (e.g. `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street`) now get a numeric suffix to disambiguate. A migration will try to rename columns.
- **Nested complex types** now use the full path: `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City` (was `BillingAddress_City`).

**Fix:** Pin existing column names explicitly so no migration rename is generated:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sa =>
    {
        sa.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
        // ... other properties
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ba =>
    {
        ba.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested complex types:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
    {
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, ba =>
        {
            ba.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

After configuring, run `dotnet ef migrations add VerifyNoChanges` — it should be empty.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on this interface (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) gains a `string logCommandText` parameter:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new: redacted SQL for safe logging
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logs (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Add this parameter to **every** method you implement on the interface — it's not just `CommandReaderExecuting`.

---

**Summary:** The `ExecuteUpdateAsync` change is the biggest win — you delete ~15 lines of expression-tree plumbing. The other two are mechanical signature/config fixes.
